04:51.000 --> 04:54.000
Various situational theories of the organization,

04:54.000 --> 04:57.000
characterizing the system orientation in general,

04:57.000 --> 04:59.000
emphasize various factors,

04:59.000 --> 05:03.000
adaptation of the organization to the requirements of technology,

05:03.000 --> 05:05.000
uncertainty of the external environment,

05:05.000 --> 05:08.000
peculiarities of decision-making processes.

05:08.000 --> 05:13.000
The last decades, marked by rapid changes in technology,

05:13.000 --> 05:17.000
increasing complexity and scientific capacity of production,

05:17.000 --> 05:22.000
its globalization and the spread of modern information technologies,

05:22.000 --> 05:25.000
gave a new powerful push to theoretical generalizations

05:25.000 --> 05:29.000
and applied scientific research in management.

05:29.000 --> 05:34.000
Ideas and concepts that form the classical theory of the organization

05:34.000 --> 05:37.000
were developed by many scientists and practitioners.

05:37.000 --> 05:42.000
One of the first attempts to analyze organizational aspects of management

05:42.000 --> 05:47.000
was undertaken by Frederick Taylor and his followers.

05:48.000 --> 05:51.000
The ideas and methods that emerge from Taylor's research

05:51.000 --> 05:54.000
are known as scientific management,

05:54.000 --> 05:59.000
in the center of which is the work carried out in the lower link of the organization.

05:59.000 --> 06:02.000
The research on the theory of the organization

06:02.000 --> 06:05.000
began to be carried out on a systematic basis

06:05.000 --> 06:10.000
from 1890 to 1940,

06:10.000 --> 06:14.000
along with deepening of the developments in scientific management.

06:14.000 --> 06:17.000
In the center of attention of these studies is the whole organization,

06:17.000 --> 06:22.000
not the work carried out by individual links or members of the organization.

06:22.000 --> 06:25.000
The principles of the organization,

06:25.000 --> 06:28.000
the criteria for the formation of organizational structures,

06:28.000 --> 06:30.000
the creation of a system of divisions,

06:30.000 --> 06:35.000
the definition of the management and delegation of rights and responsibilities were formulated.

06:35.000 --> 06:38.000
A significant contribution to the development of classical theory

06:38.000 --> 06:41.000
was the development of bureaucratic theory,

06:41.000 --> 06:44.000
the basis of which is contained in the works of Max Weber.

06:44.000 --> 06:50.000
Let's consider in more detail the key definitions of the classical theory of the organization.

06:50.000 --> 06:55.000
Under the organization, the placement and use of resources of the organization

06:55.000 --> 06:58.000
for achieving the strategic goals of the company is understood.

06:58.000 --> 07:04.000
The strategy, that is, what to do, determines the principles of the organization,

07:04.000 --> 07:05.000
that is, how to do.

07:05.000 --> 07:10.000
The process of the organization leads to the creation of an organizational structure

07:10.000 --> 07:13.000
that determines the division of tasks,

07:13.000 --> 07:17.000
as well as the placement and use of resources.

07:17.000 --> 07:22.000
There are two main aspects of the organizational process.

07:22.000 --> 07:25.000
This is the division of the organization into divisions,

07:25.000 --> 07:28.000
respectively, goals and strategies,

07:28.000 --> 07:31.000
and the relationship of powers,

07:31.000 --> 07:34.000
which bind the different levels of management

07:34.000 --> 07:39.000
and provide the possibility of distribution and coordination of tasks.

07:39.000 --> 07:44.000
The complex of formal tasks and the relationship of formal accountability

07:44.000 --> 07:48.000
determines the structure of vertical organizational control.

07:48.000 --> 07:51.000
The characteristics of the vertical structure

07:51.000 --> 07:55.000
are usually reflected in the organizational diagram,

07:55.000 --> 07:59.000
which is a visual representation of the organization structure.

07:59.000 --> 08:05.000
The organizational diagram of the Sokov-Porosly plant is shown in the following slide.

08:06.000 --> 08:10.000
The enterprise performs many different tasks,

08:10.000 --> 08:17.000
the high results of which are achieved in the case of specialization of employees.

08:17.000 --> 08:20.000
The company has four main departments

08:20.000 --> 08:27.000
of finance and accounting, human resources, production and marketing.

08:27.000 --> 08:31.000
In each of the divisions, employees perform only those tasks

08:31.000 --> 08:35.000
that are related to their specialized function.

08:35.000 --> 08:37.000
Within the production department,

08:37.000 --> 08:41.000
specialization is expressed in the division of production tasks

08:41.000 --> 08:46.000
into bottling juices, quality control and technical maintenance.

08:46.000 --> 08:50.000
The means by which the management establishes relations

08:50.000 --> 08:55.000
between levels of authority is delegating.

08:55.000 --> 08:59.000
Delegation, as a term used in the theory of management,

08:59.000 --> 09:03.000
means the transfer of tasks and authority to a person

09:03.000 --> 09:07.000
who takes responsibility for their performance.

09:07.000 --> 09:11.000
Delegation is a means by which the management distributes

09:11.000 --> 09:15.000
countless tasks among employees,

09:15.000 --> 09:19.000
which must be performed to achieve the goals of the entire organization.

09:19.000 --> 09:22.000
If a task is not delegated to another person,

09:22.000 --> 09:25.000
the manager will be forced to perform it himself.

09:25.000 --> 09:28.000
This is simply impossible in many cases,

09:28.000 --> 09:31.000
since the time and abilities of the manager are limited.

09:31.000 --> 09:36.000
Responsibility is a duty to perform the tasks

09:36.000 --> 09:40.000
and be responsible for their satisfactory solution.

09:40.000 --> 09:43.000
In fact, an individual concludes a contract with an organization

09:43.000 --> 09:46.000
to perform the tasks of this position

09:46.000 --> 09:49.000
in exchange for receiving a certain reward.

09:49.000 --> 09:53.000
Delegation is carried out only in the case of taking authority,

09:53.000 --> 09:57.000
and, in fact, responsibility cannot be delegated.

09:57.000 --> 10:00.000
The manager cannot wash away the responsibility

10:00.000 --> 10:02.000
by giving it to his subordinate.

10:02.000 --> 10:07.000
Although the person who is responsible for the solution of any task

10:07.000 --> 10:10.000
does not have to perform it personally,

10:10.000 --> 10:15.000
he remains responsible for the satisfactory completion of the work.

10:15.000 --> 10:18.000
The volume of responsibility is one of the reasons

10:18.000 --> 10:21.000
for the high salaries of the managers of the higher rank.

10:21.000 --> 10:25.000
If it is assumed that some person will take responsibility

10:25.000 --> 10:27.000
for the satisfactory completion of the task,

10:27.000 --> 10:31.000
the organization must provide him with the required resources.

10:31.000 --> 10:35.000
The management carries out this by delegating authority

10:35.000 --> 10:37.000
along with the tasks.

10:37.000 --> 10:42.000
Authority is a limited right to use the resources of the organization

10:42.000 --> 10:45.000
and direct the efforts of some of its employees

10:45.000 --> 10:48.000
to perform certain tasks.

10:48.000 --> 10:50.000
Authority is delegated to a position,

10:50.000 --> 10:54.000
not to an individual who is taking it at the moment.

10:54.000 --> 10:57.000
This is reflected in the old military saying

10:57.000 --> 11:00.000
that honor is given to the uniform, not to a person.

11:00.000 --> 11:02.000
When an individual changes his job,

11:02.000 --> 11:04.000
he loses the authority of his old position

11:04.000 --> 11:07.000
and gets the authority of a new one.

11:07.000 --> 11:09.000
However, since delegating is impossible

11:09.000 --> 11:11.000
until a person is in office,

11:11.000 --> 11:15.000
they usually talk about delegating authority to an individual,

11:15.000 --> 11:17.000
the limits of authority.

11:17.000 --> 11:19.000
According to our definition,

11:19.000 --> 11:23.000
authority is a limited right to use resources

11:23.000 --> 11:25.000
and to command people.

11:25.000 --> 11:27.000
Within the organization,

11:27.000 --> 11:30.000
these limits are usually determined by politics,

11:30.000 --> 11:34.000
procedures, rules and official instructions

11:34.000 --> 11:39.000
in written form or are transmitted by word of mouth.

11:39.000 --> 11:41.000
The persons who go beyond these limits

11:41.000 --> 11:43.000
exceed their authority,

11:43.000 --> 11:47.000
even when it is necessary to perform delegated tasks.

11:47.000 --> 11:50.000
For example, a worker authorized to work

11:50.000 --> 11:52.000
only on a certain machine

11:52.000 --> 11:54.000
would exceed his authority

11:54.000 --> 11:56.000
by moving to another machine

11:56.000 --> 11:58.000
if his own machine broke down.

11:58.000 --> 12:00.000
A more specific example would be a manager

12:00.000 --> 12:02.000
who spends money allocated for service purposes

12:02.000 --> 12:04.000
on personal needs,

12:04.000 --> 12:07.000
which exceeds the limits of his authority

12:07.000 --> 12:11.000
on the use of representative resources.

12:11.000 --> 12:14.000
In general, the limits of authority

12:14.000 --> 12:18.000
are expanding in the direction of higher levels of management.

12:18.000 --> 12:21.000
But even the authority of the higher management

12:21.000 --> 12:23.000
is limited in one way or another.

12:23.000 --> 12:25.000
The chairman of the board of directors

12:25.000 --> 12:28.000
and the president of a large open shareholder company

12:28.000 --> 12:30.000
must answer to shareholders

12:30.000 --> 12:34.000
if the costs are much higher than the total budget, for example.

12:34.000 --> 12:36.000
Higher officials of the company

12:36.000 --> 12:38.000
cannot raise their salaries,

12:38.000 --> 12:40.000
use the resources of the organization

12:40.000 --> 12:42.000
without the approval of the board of directors.

12:42.000 --> 12:44.000
Most of the authority of the manager

12:44.000 --> 12:46.000
is determined by traditions,

12:46.000 --> 12:48.000
morals, cultural stereotypes,

12:48.000 --> 12:50.000
customs of the society

12:50.000 --> 12:52.000
in which the organization functions.

12:52.000 --> 12:55.000
People obey the orders of the boss

12:55.000 --> 12:59.000
partly because it is a socially acceptable behavior.

12:59.000 --> 13:02.000
Authority and power are often confused.

13:02.000 --> 13:05.000
Authority is defined as delegated,

13:05.000 --> 13:07.000
limited,

13:07.000 --> 13:09.000
inherent in this position

13:09.000 --> 13:12.000
the right to use the resources of the organization.

13:12.000 --> 13:16.000
And power is a real ability to act

13:16.000 --> 13:19.000
or an opportunity to influence the situation.

13:19.000 --> 13:22.000
You can have power without authority.

13:22.000 --> 13:25.000
Authorities determine that a person

13:25.000 --> 13:28.000
who occupies some position has the right to do,

13:28.000 --> 13:30.000
and the authorities determine

13:30.000 --> 13:32.000
that he can really do.

13:32.000 --> 13:35.000
Linear authorities

13:35.000 --> 13:37.000
are authorities that are transferred

13:37.000 --> 13:40.000
directly from the boss to the subordinate

13:40.000 --> 13:43.000
and then to other subordinates.

13:43.000 --> 13:45.000
It is linear authorities

13:45.000 --> 13:48.000
that represent the authorized authority

13:48.000 --> 13:51.000
to direct their direct subordinates

13:51.000 --> 13:54.000
to achieve the set goals.

13:54.000 --> 13:57.000
Delegation of linear authorities

13:57.000 --> 14:00.000
creates a hierarchy of levels of management of the organization.

14:00.000 --> 14:03.000
The process of creating a hierarchy

14:03.000 --> 14:06.000
is called a scalar process.

14:06.000 --> 14:09.000
Since the authority to be controlled by people

14:09.000 --> 14:12.000
is usually transmitted through a scalar process,

14:12.000 --> 14:15.000
the resulting hierarchy is called

14:15.000 --> 14:18.000
a scalar chain or a chain of commands.

14:18.000 --> 14:21.000
The concept of the formal chain of commands

14:21.000 --> 14:24.000
was applied back in 1491 BC.

14:24.000 --> 14:27.000
The ancients saw that the best way

14:27.000 --> 14:30.000
to ensure the clarity of coordination

14:30.000 --> 14:33.000
is that the subordinate

14:33.000 --> 14:36.000
should answer only to one boss

14:36.000 --> 14:39.000
and give orders only to one boss.

14:39.000 --> 14:42.000
This principle is currently called

14:42.000 --> 14:45.000
the principle of unanimity.

14:45.000 --> 14:48.000
This is probably the oldest established principle of the organization.

14:48.000 --> 14:51.000
In an organization that adheres to this principle,

14:51.000 --> 14:54.000
all formal communications

14:54.000 --> 14:57.000
should be directed along the chain of commands.

14:57.000 --> 15:00.000
An employee cannot address any question

15:00.000 --> 15:03.000
through the head of his boss

15:03.000 --> 15:06.000
or the head of a higher rank

15:06.000 --> 15:09.000
without the permission of the boss of the intermediate level.

15:09.000 --> 15:12.000
Probably the most obvious example

15:12.000 --> 15:15.000
of the chain of commands

15:15.000 --> 15:18.000
is the hierarchy of military organizations.

15:18.000 --> 15:21.000
Military of a certain rank

15:21.000 --> 15:24.000
are easily distinguished from military of a higher or lower level

15:24.000 --> 15:27.000
by the bandaging of the badges.

15:27.000 --> 15:30.000
Here the hierarchy is really called a chain of commands.

15:30.000 --> 15:33.000
In the case of the organization,

15:33.000 --> 15:36.000
all employees from the president to the last office worker

15:36.000 --> 15:39.000
wear the same clothes,

15:39.000 --> 15:42.000
but the chain of commands still exists.

15:42.000 --> 15:45.000
Looking at the example of the plant in Roslevo-Sokol,

15:45.000 --> 15:48.000
you can see that the cashier obeys the chief accountant,

15:48.000 --> 15:51.000
who is in turn subordinate to the vice president,

15:51.000 --> 15:54.000
and the vice president obeys the president of the company.

15:54.000 --> 15:57.000
The norm of the management,

15:57.000 --> 16:00.000
the norm of the management is established

16:00.000 --> 16:03.000
by delegating linear powers.

16:03.000 --> 16:06.000
The head of the higher rank,

16:06.000 --> 16:09.000
instead of creating a chain of commands,

16:09.000 --> 16:12.000
may require that each employee

16:12.000 --> 16:15.000
reports to him personally

16:15.000 --> 16:18.000
in order to maintain, perhaps, more control.

16:18.000 --> 16:21.000
However, in practice, the inability to keep the norm of the management

16:21.000 --> 16:24.000
at a fairly low level

16:24.000 --> 16:27.000
means that the magnitude of the norm of the management

16:27.000 --> 16:30.000
varies widely.

16:30.000 --> 16:33.000
The level of management,

16:33.000 --> 16:36.000
the nature of the tasks performed,

16:36.000 --> 16:39.000
the characteristics of the subordinates and the abilities of the head

16:39.000 --> 16:42.000
all play a role in determining the number of people

16:42.000 --> 16:45.000
directly and effectively controlled by the head.

16:45.000 --> 16:48.000
A number of authors consider the best norm of the management

16:48.000 --> 16:51.000
to be from 7 to 10 subordinates.

16:51.000 --> 16:54.000
In many organizations, it is 30-40 employees or more.

16:54.000 --> 16:57.000
In general, if the manager

16:57.000 --> 17:00.000
is constantly closely interacting with the subordinates,

17:00.000 --> 17:03.000
the norm of the management should be small.

17:03.000 --> 17:06.000
And in cases when the need is absent in direct communication,

17:06.000 --> 17:09.000
the norm can be increased.

