17:37.000 --> 17:40.000
Before trying to determine the staff powers,

17:40.000 --> 17:43.000
let's briefly consider the origin of the administrative apparatus

17:43.000 --> 17:46.000
to understand why in some situations

17:46.000 --> 17:49.000
linear powers cannot meet the needs of the organization.

17:49.000 --> 17:52.000
The first concept of the staff was used

17:52.000 --> 17:55.000
in the armies of Alexander the Great,

17:55.000 --> 17:58.000
that is, in 336-323 BC.

17:58.000 --> 18:01.000
It was difficult for an officer in the heat of battle

18:01.000 --> 18:04.000
to effectively command his people

18:04.000 --> 18:07.000
and simultaneously develop strategic plans.

18:07.000 --> 18:10.000
But since planning and management

18:10.000 --> 18:13.000
are absolutely necessary for victory in any military operation,

18:13.000 --> 18:16.000
a way to ensure them should be found.

18:16.000 --> 18:19.000
It was decided to divide the task of achieving victory

18:19.000 --> 18:22.000
in the wars between two types of military specialists

18:22.000 --> 18:25.000
– officers who make plans

18:25.000 --> 18:28.000
and officers who command soldiers in battle.

18:28.000 --> 18:31.000
However, this division has created a potential problem.

18:31.000 --> 18:34.000
Since soldiers are obliged to obey the orders of all officers,

18:34.000 --> 18:37.000
they could easily get confused in a situation

18:37.000 --> 18:40.000
when the orders given to the officers on planning

18:41.000 --> 18:44.000
contradict the orders of their direct boss.

18:44.000 --> 18:47.000
To avoid this, the powers of commanding people

18:47.000 --> 18:50.000
were taken away from the planners,

18:50.000 --> 18:53.000
and since they were the assistants of the senior officer,

18:53.000 --> 18:56.000
they were called the staff.

18:56.000 --> 18:59.000
The staff apparatus of the organization can be classified

18:59.000 --> 19:02.000
into three main types –

19:02.000 --> 19:05.000
consultative apparatus, service apparatus and personal apparatus.

19:05.000 --> 19:08.000
However, in practice, it is very rare to find such a division

19:09.000 --> 19:12.000
between these types.

19:12.000 --> 19:15.000
The duty of the consultative apparatus

19:15.000 --> 19:18.000
is to consult the line leadership

19:18.000 --> 19:21.000
in their field of knowledge.

19:21.000 --> 19:24.000
This can be law, technology,

19:24.000 --> 19:27.000
training, work with personnel, etc.

19:27.000 --> 19:30.000
In any field where a consultative apparatus is used,

19:30.000 --> 19:33.000
its functions are often distributed

19:33.000 --> 19:36.000
to perform certain services.

19:36.000 --> 19:39.000
For example, the personnel department,

19:39.000 --> 19:42.000
which conducts the personal affairs of the employees,

19:42.000 --> 19:45.000
finds and checks potential candidates for work

19:45.000 --> 19:48.000
and, in some cases, supplies the line leadership

19:48.000 --> 19:51.000
the required personnel.

19:51.000 --> 19:54.000
Thus, the department performs both consultative

19:54.000 --> 19:57.000
and service functions.

19:57.000 --> 20:00.000
The personal apparatus is a variety of service apparatus

20:00.000 --> 20:03.000
that is formed when the manager

20:03.000 --> 20:06.000
is appointed to perform the tasks

20:06.000 --> 20:09.000
of the manager.

20:09.000 --> 20:12.000
In the organization, the member of this apparatus

20:12.000 --> 20:15.000
has no powers,

20:15.000 --> 20:18.000
he acts only on the instructions of the manager.

20:18.000 --> 20:21.000
However, he can have great power.

20:21.000 --> 20:24.000
To understand the concept of the apparatus in modern organizations,

20:24.000 --> 20:27.000
it is necessary to consider the nature of the powers delegated to him.

20:27.000 --> 20:30.000
Staff powers can be limited,

20:30.000 --> 20:33.000
but they can be purely consultative

20:33.000 --> 20:36.000
or so common that the border between them

20:36.000 --> 20:39.000
and the line duties almost disappears.

20:39.000 --> 20:42.000
Let's consider the basic types of staff powers

20:42.000 --> 20:45.000
and the basis of their application.

20:45.000 --> 20:48.000
When the staff powers are reduced to the recommended powers,

20:48.000 --> 20:51.000
it is assumed that the line leadership

20:51.000 --> 20:54.000
will consult the consultative apparatus

20:54.000 --> 20:57.000
when it needs its knowledge.

20:58.000 --> 21:01.000
But the line leaders are not obliged to do so.

21:01.000 --> 21:04.000
They can solve the problem in their own way,

21:04.000 --> 21:07.000
without even making the apparatus known.

21:07.000 --> 21:10.000
When the staff powers of the apparatus are recommended,

21:10.000 --> 21:13.000
it often has to spend time

21:13.000 --> 21:16.000
convincing the line leaders

21:16.000 --> 21:19.000
about the value of its services and proposals.

21:19.000 --> 21:22.000
Even if they appealed for advice to the apparatus

21:22.000 --> 21:25.000
and it was accepted, the line leaders can still neglect it,

21:26.000 --> 21:29.000
which can undoubtedly lead to conflicts

21:29.000 --> 21:32.000
between the line leadership and the administrative and management apparatus.

21:32.000 --> 21:35.000
Since the apparatus may experience difficulties

21:35.000 --> 21:38.000
in communication with the line leadership,

21:38.000 --> 21:41.000
the company sometimes expands the powers of the apparatus

21:41.000 --> 21:44.000
to mandatory agreements.

21:44.000 --> 21:47.000
When the agreements are mandatory,

21:47.000 --> 21:50.000
the line leadership must discuss the appropriate situation

21:50.000 --> 21:53.000
with the staff apparatus before taking any action.

21:54.000 --> 21:57.000
However, the line leaders are not obliged

21:57.000 --> 22:00.000
to follow the recommendations of the apparatus.

22:00.000 --> 22:03.000
The higher management can expand the powers of the apparatus,

22:03.000 --> 22:06.000
giving it the right to reject the decisions of the line leadership.

22:06.000 --> 22:09.000
The goal of parallel powers

22:09.000 --> 22:12.000
is to establish a control system

22:12.000 --> 22:15.000
to balance power

22:15.000 --> 22:18.000
and prevent gross mistakes.

22:18.000 --> 22:21.000
In many companies,

22:21.000 --> 22:24.000
parallel powers are used

22:24.000 --> 22:27.000
to control financial expenses,

22:27.000 --> 22:30.000
which requires two signatures

22:30.000 --> 22:33.000
in the case of all major purchases.

22:33.000 --> 22:36.000
The apparatus, which has functional powers,

22:36.000 --> 22:39.000
can offer and prohibit some actions

22:39.000 --> 22:42.000
in the field of its competence.

22:42.000 --> 22:45.000
In fact, the line powers of the president of the organization

22:45.000 --> 22:48.000
are implemented through the apparatus,

22:48.000 --> 22:51.000
but the apparatus is not able to do this.

22:51.000 --> 22:54.000
The functional powers eliminate the difference

22:54.000 --> 22:57.000
between the line and the staff powers

22:57.000 --> 23:00.000
for all practical purposes.

23:00.000 --> 23:03.000
In large organizations,

23:03.000 --> 23:06.000
the apparatus can consist of many people.

23:06.000 --> 23:09.000
In such situations, the apparatus is a division

23:09.000 --> 23:12.000
with more than one level of management.

23:12.000 --> 23:15.000
That is, the staff apparatus itself has a linear organization

23:15.000 --> 23:18.000
Delegation requires effective communication,

23:18.000 --> 23:21.000
and the subordinates must understand exactly

23:21.000 --> 23:24.000
what the leader wants.

23:24.000 --> 23:27.000
Delegation is also related to motivation,

23:27.000 --> 23:30.000
influence and leadership.

23:30.000 --> 23:33.000
The leader must make the subordinates

23:33.000 --> 23:36.000
to effectively perform their tasks.

23:36.000 --> 23:39.000
As in all processes of information exchange

23:39.000 --> 23:42.000
and influence, both sides have a significant

23:42.000 --> 23:45.000
role in achieving success.

23:45.000 --> 23:48.000
Taking this into account, William Newman listed

23:48.000 --> 23:51.000
a number of reasons why leaders may

23:51.000 --> 23:54.000
reluctantly delegate powers,

23:54.000 --> 23:57.000
and subordinates will avoid additional responsibility.

23:57.000 --> 24:00.000
So, the reasons for the leaders' reluctance

24:00.000 --> 24:03.000
to delegate powers.

24:03.000 --> 24:06.000
This is a delusion, I will do it better.

24:06.000 --> 24:09.000
This is the lack of ability to lead,

24:10.000 --> 24:13.000
lack of trust in subordinates,

24:13.000 --> 24:16.000
fear of risk, lack of election control

24:16.000 --> 24:19.000
to warn the leadership about possible dangers.

24:19.000 --> 24:22.000
Subordinates avoid responsibility

24:22.000 --> 24:25.000
and block the process of delegating

24:25.000 --> 24:28.000
for the following reasons.

24:28.000 --> 24:31.000
Subordinates may find it more convenient to ask the boss

24:31.000 --> 24:34.000
what to do than to solve the problem themselves.

24:34.000 --> 24:37.000
Subordinates are also afraid of criticism for mistakes.

24:37.000 --> 24:40.000
The more responsibility, the more likely such a mistake.

24:40.000 --> 24:43.000
Subordinates have no information

24:43.000 --> 24:46.000
or resources necessary for the task.

24:46.000 --> 24:49.000
Subordinates may also lack confidence in themselves

24:49.000 --> 24:52.000
or lack positive incentives

24:52.000 --> 24:55.000
to additional responsibility.

24:55.000 --> 24:58.000
To make delegating effective,

24:58.000 --> 25:01.000
there must be a correspondence between powers and responsibility.

25:01.000 --> 25:04.000
That is, the leadership must delegate

25:04.000 --> 25:07.000
powers sufficient for the fulfillment of all tasks

25:07.000 --> 25:10.000
for which he took responsibility.

25:10.000 --> 25:13.000
This is called the principle of correspondence.

25:13.000 --> 25:16.000
High responsibility means more work

25:16.000 --> 25:19.000
and more risk for the person taking it.

25:19.000 --> 25:22.000
Expanding the responsibility of subordinates

25:22.000 --> 25:25.000
should be supported by a system of stimulation,

25:25.000 --> 25:28.000
which provides them with rewards

25:28.000 --> 25:31.000
for taking this time.

25:31.000 --> 25:34.000
Recent studies have shown

25:34.000 --> 25:37.000
that employees have less motivation for work

25:37.000 --> 25:40.000
if they think they give more to the organization

25:40.000 --> 25:43.000
than they receive from it.

25:43.000 --> 25:46.000
As a result, the absence of positive incentives

25:46.000 --> 25:49.000
to take on additional responsibility

25:49.000 --> 25:52.000
can block reasonable attempts to distribute powers.

25:52.000 --> 25:55.000
Do the practical task number two.

25:55.000 --> 25:58.000
Think about how effective the process of delegating

25:58.000 --> 26:01.000
powers in your organization is.

26:01.000 --> 26:04.000
What can you offer to eliminate the reasons

26:04.000 --> 26:07.000
that block delegating?

26:07.000 --> 26:10.000
Centralization and decentralization

26:10.000 --> 26:13.000
Our next topic is centralization and decentralization.

26:13.000 --> 26:16.000
Organizations in which the leadership of the higher link

26:16.000 --> 26:19.000
leaves behind most of the powers

26:19.000 --> 26:22.000
necessary for making the most important decisions

26:22.000 --> 26:25.000
are called centralized.

26:25.000 --> 26:28.000
Decentralized organizations

26:28.000 --> 26:31.000
are such organizations

26:31.000 --> 26:34.000
in which powers are distributed

26:34.000 --> 26:37.000
at the lowest levels of management.

26:37.000 --> 26:40.000
In highly decentralized organizations,

26:40.000 --> 26:43.000
the managers of the middle link

26:43.000 --> 26:46.000
have very great powers in specific areas of activity.

26:46.000 --> 26:49.000
However, in practice, there are no fully centralized

26:49.000 --> 26:52.000
or decentralized organizations.

26:52.000 --> 26:55.000
Such organizations are only the limit points

26:55.000 --> 26:58.000
of a certain continuum

26:58.000 --> 27:01.000
between which all types of structures

27:01.000 --> 27:04.000
that meet in practice lie.

27:04.000 --> 27:07.000
Therefore, any organization can be called centralized

27:07.000 --> 27:10.000
or decentralized only in comparison

27:10.000 --> 27:13.000
with other organizations or in comparison with itself,

27:13.000 --> 27:16.000
but in other periods.

27:16.000 --> 27:19.000
It is possible to determine the level of centralization

27:19.000 --> 27:22.000
in comparison with others

27:22.000 --> 27:25.000
by following its characteristics.

27:25.000 --> 27:28.000
The first of them is the number of decisions

27:28.000 --> 27:31.000
made at the lowest levels of management.

27:31.000 --> 27:34.000
The more decisions made by the lower managers,

27:34.000 --> 27:37.000
the greater the degree of decentralization.

27:37.000 --> 27:40.000
The second characteristic is the importance of decisions

27:40.000 --> 27:43.000
made at the lowest levels.

27:43.000 --> 27:46.000
In a decentralized organization,

27:46.000 --> 27:49.000
the managers of the middle and lower links

27:49.000 --> 27:52.000
can make decisions related to the costs

27:52.000 --> 27:55.000
of significant material and labor resources

27:55.000 --> 27:58.000
or the direction of the organization's activity

27:58.000 --> 28:01.000
in a new direction.

28:01.000 --> 28:04.000
The next characteristic is the consequences of decisions

28:04.000 --> 28:07.000
made at the lowest levels.

28:07.000 --> 28:10.000
If the managers of the middle and lower links

28:10.000 --> 28:13.000
can make decisions affecting more than one function,

28:13.000 --> 28:16.000
then the organization is, apparently, decentralized.

28:17.000 --> 28:20.000
The next characteristic is the number of control

28:20.000 --> 28:23.000
over the work of subordinates.

28:23.000 --> 28:26.000
In a highly decentralized organization,

28:26.000 --> 28:29.000
the management of the higher link rarely checks

28:29.000 --> 28:32.000
the daily decisions of its subordinates.

28:32.000 --> 28:35.000
Based on the assumption that all these decisions are correct,

28:35.000 --> 28:38.000
the assessment of the actions of the management

28:38.000 --> 28:41.000
is based on the total achieved results,

28:41.000 --> 28:44.000
profitability and growth of the organization.

28:44.000 --> 28:47.000
Within the same organization,

28:47.000 --> 28:50.000
some departments can be more centralized than others.

28:50.000 --> 28:53.000
For example, in the McDonald's restaurant network,

28:53.000 --> 28:56.000
the managers of the restaurants have almost unlimited power

28:56.000 --> 28:59.000
to make decisions regarding their staff

28:59.000 --> 29:02.000
and some powers in the selection of purchased products.

29:02.000 --> 29:05.000
In this company, decisions on the placement

29:05.000 --> 29:08.000
of new restaurants and stores

29:08.000 --> 29:11.000
are made in the middle management links,

29:11.000 --> 29:14.000
while decisions determining the price level

29:14.000 --> 29:17.000
and the release of new goods

29:17.000 --> 29:20.000
are made only by the higher management.

29:20.000 --> 29:23.000
In ordinary hospitals, administrative functions

29:23.000 --> 29:26.000
have a high degree of centralization,

29:26.000 --> 29:29.000
but the medical staff and, first of all,

29:29.000 --> 29:32.000
the doctors are almost completely autonomous

29:32.000 --> 29:35.000
and independent in their actions.

29:35.000 --> 29:38.000
In large part of decentralized organizations,

29:38.000 --> 29:41.000
the higher management leaves the right

29:41.000 --> 29:44.000
to make decisions on issues such as

29:44.000 --> 29:47.000
determining the common goals and tasks of the organization,

29:47.000 --> 29:50.000
strategic planning,

29:50.000 --> 29:53.000
formulation of company policies in various areas,

29:53.000 --> 29:56.000
development of the company's financial and accounting system.

29:56.000 --> 29:59.000
Most corporations have a decentralized organization.

29:59.000 --> 30:02.000
Their general structure is based on the principle

30:02.000 --> 30:05.000
of federal decentralization,

30:05.000 --> 30:08.000
in which the managers of the most important departments

30:08.000 --> 30:11.000
can act almost completely autonomously

30:11.000 --> 30:14.000
in everything that concerns the production of their products.

30:14.000 --> 30:17.000
Both centralization and decentralization

30:17.000 --> 30:20.000
have their disadvantages and advantages,

30:20.000 --> 30:23.000
the ratio of which is determined by external

30:23.000 --> 30:26.000
and internal variables.

30:26.000 --> 30:29.000
The advantages of centralization include

30:29.000 --> 30:32.000
the improvement of control and coordination

30:32.000 --> 30:35.000
of specialized independent functions,

30:35.000 --> 30:38.000
the reduction of the number and scale of error decisions

30:38.000 --> 30:41.000
made by less experienced managers,

30:41.000 --> 30:44.000
the absence of a situation in which

30:44.000 --> 30:47.000
some departments of the organization grow and develop

30:47.000 --> 30:50.000
due to other departments or organizations in general,

30:50.000 --> 30:53.000
and the experience and knowledge of the staff

30:53.000 --> 30:56.000
of the central administrative body

30:57.000 --> 31:00.000
The advantages of decentralization include

31:00.000 --> 31:03.000
simplification of the decision-making process.

31:03.000 --> 31:06.000
Decisions are made by the manager

31:06.000 --> 31:09.000
who is closest to the problem

31:09.000 --> 31:12.000
and, therefore, knows it best.

31:12.000 --> 31:15.000
Decentralization stimulates initiative

31:15.000 --> 31:18.000
and allows the personality to identify itself with the organization.

31:18.000 --> 31:21.000
The manager can feel the same enthusiasm

31:21.000 --> 31:24.000
in his department as independent entrepreneurs

31:25.000 --> 31:28.000
in all their business.

31:28.000 --> 31:31.000
Decentralization helps to prepare the young manager

31:31.000 --> 31:34.000
for higher positions,

31:34.000 --> 31:37.000
giving him the opportunity to make important decisions

31:37.000 --> 31:40.000
at the very beginning of his career.

31:40.000 --> 31:43.000
The disadvantages of centralization are that

31:43.000 --> 31:46.000
it closes the way to the benefits of decentralization.

31:46.000 --> 31:49.000
And vice versa.

31:49.000 --> 31:52.000
The manager must analyze the situation in the organization

31:52.000 --> 31:55.000
and choose the level of decision-making

31:55.000 --> 31:58.000
that best meets its needs.

31:58.000 --> 32:01.000
The need to make radical changes

32:01.000 --> 32:04.000
and a high level of uncertainty of the external environment

32:04.000 --> 32:07.000
are favored by decentralization.

32:07.000 --> 32:10.000
The ratio of centralization and decentralization

32:10.000 --> 32:13.000
should be adequate for the firm's strategy.

32:13.000 --> 32:16.000
During a crisis or in cases

32:16.000 --> 32:19.000
when direct threats arise,

32:20.000 --> 32:23.000
the power and authority, as a rule,

32:23.000 --> 32:26.000
are concentrated in the hands of the top managers of the organization.

32:26.000 --> 32:29.000
Perform the practical task number 3.

32:29.000 --> 32:32.000
Evaluate the ratio of centralization and decentralization

32:32.000 --> 32:35.000
in your company.

32:35.000 --> 32:38.000
What factors have a significant impact on this process?

32:43.000 --> 32:46.000
Our next topic is the design of the organizational structure.

32:47.000 --> 32:50.000
The best structure is the one that best allows the organization

32:50.000 --> 32:53.000
to interact effectively with the external environment,

32:53.000 --> 32:56.000
to distribute and direct the efforts of its employees

32:56.000 --> 32:59.000
productively and purposefully

32:59.000 --> 33:02.000
and thus meet the needs of the clients

33:02.000 --> 33:05.000
and achieve their goals with high efficiency.

33:05.000 --> 33:08.000
The design should be based on the strategic plans of the organization.

33:08.000 --> 33:11.000
This approach was designed

33:11.000 --> 33:14.000
to be able to meet the needs of the organization

33:14.000 --> 33:17.000
This approach was proposed by Alfred Chandler,

33:17.000 --> 33:20.000
who for many years studied the changes

33:20.000 --> 33:23.000
in organizational structures of companies

33:23.000 --> 33:26.000
such as General Motors and DuPont.

33:26.000 --> 33:29.000
His famous principle says

33:29.000 --> 33:32.000
that the strategy determines the structure.

33:32.000 --> 33:35.000
This means that the structure of the organization

33:35.000 --> 33:38.000
should be such to ensure the implementation of its strategy.

33:38.000 --> 33:41.000
Since over time, strategies change,

33:41.000 --> 33:44.000
it will be necessary to make appropriate changes

33:44.000 --> 33:47.000
in organizational structures.

33:47.000 --> 33:50.000
According to the classical theory of organization,

33:50.000 --> 33:53.000
the structure of the organization should be developed from top to bottom.

33:53.000 --> 33:56.000
At the beginning, the managers should divide the organization

33:56.000 --> 33:59.000
into wide areas,

33:59.000 --> 34:02.000
then set specific tasks,

34:02.000 --> 34:05.000
just like in planning,

34:05.000 --> 34:08.000
first general tasks are formed,

34:08.000 --> 34:11.000
then the specific plans are formed,

34:11.000 --> 34:14.000
and finally the organizational design stages.

34:14.000 --> 34:17.000
The sequence of actions will be as follows.

34:17.000 --> 34:20.000
First, divide the organization horizontally

34:20.000 --> 34:23.000
into wide blocks corresponding

34:23.000 --> 34:26.000
to the most important areas of activity

34:26.000 --> 34:29.000
in the implementation of the strategy.

34:29.000 --> 34:32.000
Decide which types of activities should be performed

34:32.000 --> 34:35.000
by linear units, and which by staff units.

34:35.000 --> 34:38.000
Third, determine the ratio of powers of various positions.

34:38.000 --> 34:41.000
At the same time, the management sets a chain of commands

34:41.000 --> 34:44.000
if necessary,

34:44.000 --> 34:47.000
to make further divisions into smaller organizational units

34:47.000 --> 34:50.000
to more effectively use specialization

34:50.000 --> 34:53.000
and avoid overloading the management.

34:55.000 --> 34:58.000
Third, determine the duties

34:58.000 --> 35:01.000
as a combination of certain tasks and functions

35:01.000 --> 35:04.000
and assign them to specific persons.

35:04.000 --> 35:07.000
In organizations whose activity is largely connected

35:07.000 --> 35:10.000
with technology,

35:10.000 --> 35:13.000
the management even develops specific tasks

35:13.000 --> 35:16.000
and assigns them to the direct performers,

35:16.000 --> 35:19.000
who are responsible for their satisfactory performance.

35:20.000 --> 35:23.000
It is important to understand that the organizational structure

35:23.000 --> 35:26.000
that has emerged as a result of the development

35:26.000 --> 35:29.000
is an unhardened form, similar to the frame of a building.

35:29.000 --> 35:32.000
Since organizational structures are based on plans,

35:33.000 --> 35:36.000
significant changes in the plans may require

35:36.000 --> 35:39.000
corresponding changes in the structure.

35:39.000 --> 35:42.000
In fact, in existing organizations,

35:42.000 --> 35:45.000
the process of changing the organizational structure

35:45.000 --> 35:48.000
should be treated as a reorganization,

35:48.000 --> 35:51.000
since this process, like all functions of the organization,

35:51.000 --> 35:54.000
is endless.

35:54.000 --> 35:57.000
Currently, successfully functioning organizations

35:57.000 --> 36:00.000
regularly assess the degree of adequacy

36:00.000 --> 36:03.000
of their organizational structures

36:03.000 --> 36:06.000
and change them as required by external conditions.

36:06.000 --> 36:09.000
The requirements of the external environment,

36:09.000 --> 36:12.000
in turn, are determined during planning and control.

36:12.000 --> 36:15.000
The development of formal rules, policies, instructions, procedures,

36:15.000 --> 36:18.000
descriptions of work, instructions,

36:18.000 --> 36:21.000
in accordance with which management and control

36:21.000 --> 36:24.000
over the activities of employees is carried out

36:24.000 --> 36:27.000
is called formalization.

36:28.000 --> 36:31.000
Such documents complement the organizational scheme,

36:31.000 --> 36:34.000
describing tasks, distributing responsibility

36:34.000 --> 36:37.000
and authority for making management decisions.

36:37.000 --> 36:40.000
The widespread use of such documents

36:40.000 --> 36:43.000
is an integral part of the bureaucratic management model,

36:43.000 --> 36:46.000
the first systematically developed model

36:46.000 --> 36:49.000
of the organizational structure,

36:49.000 --> 36:52.000
which remains its main and dominant form.

36:52.000 --> 36:55.000
The word bureaucracy is usually mentioned

36:56.000 --> 36:59.000
in the picture of the office work,

36:59.000 --> 37:02.000
bad work, useless activity,

37:02.000 --> 37:05.000
long-term expectations to receive certificates

37:05.000 --> 37:08.000
or forms that have long been canceled.

37:08.000 --> 37:11.000
All this really happens.

37:11.000 --> 37:14.000
However, the root cause of all these negative phenomena

37:14.000 --> 37:17.000
is not bureaucracy as such,

37:17.000 --> 37:20.000
but the lack of implementation of the rules of work

37:20.000 --> 37:23.000
and the goals of the organization,

37:23.000 --> 37:26.000
the behavior of employees,

37:26.000 --> 37:29.000
the inappropriate rules and tasks of the organization.

37:29.000 --> 37:32.000
The concept of bureaucracy,

37:32.000 --> 37:35.000
originally formulated by the German sociologist

37:35.000 --> 37:38.000
Max Weber in the early 1900s,

37:38.000 --> 37:41.000
is ideally one of the most useful ideas

37:41.000 --> 37:44.000
in the history of mankind.

37:44.000 --> 37:47.000
Weber's theory did not contain descriptions

37:47.000 --> 37:50.000
of specific organizations.

37:50.000 --> 37:53.000
The idea of a bureaucracy is more like a normative model,

37:53.000 --> 37:56.000
as an ideal to which organizations should strive.

37:56.000 --> 37:59.000
This is clear from the table,

37:59.000 --> 38:02.000
where the characteristics of the system

38:02.000 --> 38:05.000
called Weber's rational bureaucracy

38:05.000 --> 38:08.000
are given in a sum.

38:08.000 --> 38:11.000
The following characteristics are suitable for rational bureaucracy.

38:11.000 --> 38:14.000
First of all, this is a clear division of labor,

38:14.000 --> 38:17.000
which leads to the appearance of highly qualified specialists

38:17.000 --> 38:20.000
in each position.

38:20.000 --> 38:23.000
This is the hierarchy of management levels,

38:23.000 --> 38:26.000
in which each lower level is controlled by the higher one

38:26.000 --> 38:29.000
and subordinated to it.

38:29.000 --> 38:32.000
This is the presence of a interconnected system

38:32.000 --> 38:35.000
of generalized formal rules and standards,

38:35.000 --> 38:38.000
ensuring uniformity of the performance of its responsibilities

38:38.000 --> 38:41.000
and coordination of various tasks.

38:41.000 --> 38:44.000
This is the spirit of formal indifference,

38:44.000 --> 38:47.000
with which official persons perform their official duties

38:47.000 --> 38:50.000
and the implementation of hiring

38:50.000 --> 38:53.000
in strict accordance with the technical and qualification requirements

38:53.000 --> 38:56.000
protected from employees from arbitrary dismissals.

38:56.000 --> 38:59.000
Thus, the bureaucratic organizational structure

38:59.000 --> 39:02.000
is characterized by a high degree of division of labor,

39:02.000 --> 39:05.000
a developed hierarchy of management,

39:05.000 --> 39:08.000
a chain of commands,

39:08.000 --> 39:11.000
the presence of numerous rules and standards of personnel behavior,

39:11.000 --> 39:14.000
a selection of personnel

39:14.000 --> 39:17.000
according to their business and professional qualities.

39:17.000 --> 39:20.000
Weber called such a structure rational,

39:20.000 --> 39:23.000
because it is assumed that decisions made by the bureaucracy

39:23.000 --> 39:26.000
have an objective nature.

39:26.000 --> 39:29.000
Weber believed that the personal preferences

39:29.000 --> 39:32.000
of the owners of the organization and its employees

39:32.000 --> 39:35.000
should not contradict the goals of the organization.

39:35.000 --> 39:38.000
These ideas did not coincide with the practice of working

39:38.000 --> 39:41.000
of most organizations until 1900.

39:41.000 --> 39:44.000
Bureaucracy is often called a classical

39:44.000 --> 39:47.000
or traditional organizational structure.

39:47.000 --> 39:50.000
Most modern organizations

39:50.000 --> 39:53.000
are variants of bureaucracy.

39:53.000 --> 39:56.000
The objectivity of decisions made

39:56.000 --> 39:59.000
allows the bureaucracy to adapt to the changes.

39:59.000 --> 40:02.000
Promotion of employees based on their competencies

40:02.000 --> 40:05.000
allows to ensure constant and consistent

40:05.000 --> 40:08.000
influx of highly qualified and talented technical specialists

40:08.000 --> 40:11.000
and administrative workers.

40:11.000 --> 40:14.000
However, bureaucracy has often been severely criticized.

40:14.000 --> 40:17.000
The difficulties arising in bureaucratic structures

40:17.000 --> 40:20.000
are associated with an increase in the significance

40:20.000 --> 40:23.000
of standardized rules and procedures,

40:23.000 --> 40:26.000
those norms that ensure the proper execution

40:26.000 --> 40:29.000
of their tasks by employees.

40:29.000 --> 40:32.000
The organization, at the same time,

40:33.000 --> 40:36.000
loses the flexibility of behavior.

40:36.000 --> 40:39.000
Departmentalization means the process of dividing the organization

40:39.000 --> 40:42.000
into separate blocks,

40:42.000 --> 40:45.000
which can be called departments,

40:45.000 --> 40:48.000
branches, or sectors.

40:48.000 --> 40:51.000
Functional departmentalization is the process

40:51.000 --> 40:54.000
of dividing the organization into separate elements,

40:54.000 --> 40:57.000
each of which has its own clearly defined

40:57.000 --> 41:00.000
specific task and responsibilities.

41:00.000 --> 41:03.000
In principle, the creation of a functional structure

41:03.000 --> 41:06.000
is reduced to a grouping of staff

41:06.000 --> 41:09.000
on the broad tasks they perform.

41:09.000 --> 41:12.000
In companies that process industry,

41:12.000 --> 41:15.000
this is a division by technology of mass production.

41:15.000 --> 41:18.000
Traditional functional blocks of a company

41:18.000 --> 41:21.000
are departments of production, marketing, and finance.

41:23.000 --> 41:26.000
In organizations not related to business,

41:26.000 --> 41:29.000
the names of functional departments

41:29.000 --> 41:32.000
are the most diverse.

41:32.000 --> 41:35.000
In the army, for example,

41:35.000 --> 41:38.000
there are infantry, artillery, and armored units.

41:38.000 --> 41:41.000
In hospitals there are administrative and medical departments.

41:41.000 --> 41:44.000
If the size of all organizations or this department is large,

41:44.000 --> 41:47.000
then the main functional departments

41:47.000 --> 41:50.000
can be divided into smaller functional departments.

41:50.000 --> 41:53.000
The structure of the organization,

41:53.000 --> 41:56.000
the functional departments of which are divided

41:56.000 --> 41:59.000
into secondary units, are the most important.

41:59.000 --> 42:02.000
A functional structure stimulates

42:02.000 --> 42:05.000
business and professional specialization,

42:05.000 --> 42:08.000
reduces duplication of efforts

42:08.000 --> 42:11.000
and consumption of material resources,

42:11.000 --> 42:14.000
improves coordination in functional areas.

42:14.000 --> 42:17.000
A well-known example of regional organizational structures

42:17.000 --> 42:20.000
can be household organizations of large companies.

42:20.000 --> 42:23.000
An example of the use of a regional structure

42:24.000 --> 42:27.000
outside of a commercial organization

42:27.000 --> 42:30.000
can be the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Russia.

42:30.000 --> 42:33.000
It is known to the embassies and consulates of Russia around the world.

42:33.000 --> 42:36.000
Many other government institutions,

42:36.000 --> 42:39.000
especially those such as the Tax Service,

42:39.000 --> 42:42.000
which are constantly dealing with their clients,

42:42.000 --> 42:45.000
also apply a regional structure.

42:45.000 --> 42:48.000
The relative advantages and disadvantages

42:48.000 --> 42:51.000
of regional organizational structures are similar to those

42:51.000 --> 42:54.000
of products and consumers.

42:54.000 --> 42:57.000
Various types of divisional structures

42:57.000 --> 43:00.000
have the same advantages and disadvantages

43:00.000 --> 43:03.000
because they have the same goal

43:03.000 --> 43:06.000
to ensure a more effective reaction of the organization

43:06.000 --> 43:09.000
to one or another factor of the environment.

43:09.000 --> 43:12.000
A product structure allows

43:12.000 --> 43:15.000
to easily cope with the development of new types of products

43:15.000 --> 43:18.000
based on the concept of competition,

43:18.000 --> 43:21.000
improvement of technology

43:21.000 --> 43:24.000
or satisfaction of the consumer's needs.

43:24.000 --> 43:27.000
A regional structure allows the organization

43:27.000 --> 43:30.000
to more effectively take into account local legislation,

43:30.000 --> 43:33.000
the social and economic system and markets

43:33.000 --> 43:36.000
as the geographical expansion of its market zones.

43:36.000 --> 43:39.000
As for the structure oriented to the consumer,

43:39.000 --> 43:42.000
it gives the organization the opportunity

43:42.000 --> 43:45.000
to most effectively take into account the requests of those consumers

43:45.000 --> 43:48.000
from whom it depends the most.

43:48.000 --> 43:51.000
Thus, the choice of a divisional structure

43:51.000 --> 43:54.000
should be based on which of these factors

43:54.000 --> 43:57.000
is the most important

43:57.000 --> 44:00.000
in terms of ensuring the implementation

44:00.000 --> 44:03.000
of the organization's strategic plans and achieving its goals.

