Perform the practical task number 5.

49:10.000 --> 49:13.000
It is a question of the technical situation

49:13.000 --> 49:16.000
that has developed in one of the Russian metallurgical companies

49:16.000 --> 49:19.000
and the answer to the questions of the case.

49:22.000 --> 49:25.000
Since the 1960s, some organizations

49:25.000 --> 49:28.000
have faced such a situation

49:28.000 --> 49:31.000
when the external conditions of their activities

49:31.000 --> 49:34.000
have changed so quickly.

49:34.000 --> 49:37.000
Projects have become so complex,

49:37.000 --> 49:40.000
that the organizational structure

49:40.000 --> 49:43.000
of the company has become more complex.

49:43.000 --> 49:46.000
The structure of the traditional organizational structure,

49:46.000 --> 49:49.000
especially where the chain of command is long,

49:49.000 --> 49:52.000
can slow down the interaction

49:52.000 --> 49:55.000
and the process of development of solutions

49:55.000 --> 49:58.000
to such an extent that the organization

49:58.000 --> 50:01.000
could no longer effectively react to the changes.

50:01.000 --> 50:04.000
In order for organizations to be able

50:04.000 --> 50:07.000
to implement new technology,

50:07.000 --> 50:10.000
adaptive organizational structures have been developed.

50:10.000 --> 50:13.000
The structures are called adaptive

50:13.000 --> 50:16.000
because they can be quickly modified

50:16.000 --> 50:19.000
in accordance with the changes in the environment

50:19.000 --> 50:22.000
and the needs of the organization itself.

50:22.000 --> 50:25.000
Another name for these more flexible systems

50:25.000 --> 50:28.000
is organic structures.

50:28.000 --> 50:31.000
It is connected with their ability

50:31.000 --> 50:34.000
to adapt to the changes in the environment

50:34.000 --> 50:37.000
and to adapt to the changes in the environment

50:37.000 --> 50:40.000
in accordance with the changes in the environment.

50:40.000 --> 50:43.000
Organic or adaptive structures

50:43.000 --> 50:46.000
are not just some kind of variation of bureaucracy

50:46.000 --> 50:49.000
as is the divisional structure.

50:49.000 --> 50:52.000
The organic structure is built on the goals

50:52.000 --> 50:55.000
and assumptions radically different

50:55.000 --> 50:58.000
from those that lie at the base of bureaucracy.

50:58.000 --> 51:01.000
Organic structures are built on the goals

51:01.000 --> 51:04.000
and assumptions radically different

51:04.000 --> 51:07.000
from those that lie at the base of bureaucracy.

51:07.000 --> 51:10.000
Each specialist solves his task

51:10.000 --> 51:13.000
as something separate from the real tasks

51:13.000 --> 51:16.000
before the organization as a whole.

51:16.000 --> 51:19.000
In the case of an organic structure,

51:19.000 --> 51:22.000
employees must solve their specific tasks

51:22.000 --> 51:25.000
in the light of the tasks of the company as a whole.

51:25.000 --> 51:28.000
This is because they must be constantly reviewed

51:28.000 --> 51:31.000
as a result of interaction with other participants

51:31.000 --> 51:34.000
in solving this task.

51:34.000 --> 51:37.000
This interaction occurs both vertically and horizontally.

51:37.000 --> 51:40.000
Interaction between employees of different ranks

51:40.000 --> 51:43.000
is like a consultation of two colleagues

51:43.000 --> 51:46.000
than an order from the boss to a subordinate.

51:46.000 --> 51:49.000
It should be noted that organic and bureaucratic structures

51:49.000 --> 51:52.000
are just two extreme points in the continuum of structures,

51:53.000 --> 51:56.000
and the real structures of real organizations

51:56.000 --> 51:59.000
lie between them, having signs of both bureaucratic

51:59.000 --> 52:02.000
and organic structures in different ratios.

52:02.000 --> 52:05.000
have signs of both bureaucratic and organic structures in different ratios.

52:05.000 --> 52:08.000
In addition, it often happens that

52:08.000 --> 52:11.000
various divisions within one organization

52:11.000 --> 52:14.000
have different structures.

52:14.000 --> 52:17.000
Often, for example, the management of an organization

52:17.000 --> 52:20.000
uses mechanical, that is, bureaucratic structures

52:21.000 --> 52:24.000
and in scientific and research organizations — organic structures.

52:24.000 --> 52:27.000
The dependence of the structure of an organization

52:27.000 --> 52:30.000
on the pace of the environment is shown in the following slide.

52:30.000 --> 52:33.000
In order to effectively manage large-scale projects

52:33.000 --> 52:36.000
of limited duration,

52:36.000 --> 52:39.000
for example, the construction of a building

52:39.000 --> 52:42.000
or the launch of a spaceship,

52:42.000 --> 52:45.000
more and more organizations began to use

52:45.000 --> 52:48.000
special project organization.

52:48.000 --> 52:51.000
A project organization is a temporary structure

52:51.000 --> 52:54.000
created to solve a specific task.

52:54.000 --> 52:57.000
Its purpose is to bring together

52:57.000 --> 53:00.000
the most qualified employees of the organization

53:00.000 --> 53:03.000
to carry out a complex project

53:03.000 --> 53:06.000
in the set time and set quality level,

53:06.000 --> 53:09.000
without going beyond the set cost.

53:09.000 --> 53:12.000
When the project is completed, the team is disbanded,

53:12.000 --> 53:15.000
its members move on to a new project,

53:15.000 --> 53:18.000
return to their permanent work in their home department

53:18.000 --> 53:21.000
or leave the organization.

53:21.000 --> 53:24.000
The main advantage of a project organization

53:24.000 --> 53:27.000
is that it concentrates all efforts

53:27.000 --> 53:30.000
on solving a single task.

53:30.000 --> 53:33.000
While the head of a regular department

53:33.000 --> 53:36.000
must be split between several projects at the same time,

53:36.000 --> 53:39.000
the project manager focuses

53:39.000 --> 53:42.000
exclusively on him.

53:42.000 --> 53:45.000
In the so-called clean or combined project structures,

53:45.000 --> 53:48.000
a temporary group of specialists

53:48.000 --> 53:51.000
is essentially a reduced-scale copy

53:51.000 --> 53:54.000
of the permanent functional structure

53:54.000 --> 53:57.000
of the given organization.

53:57.000 --> 54:00.000
In this case, the project manager

54:00.000 --> 54:03.000
is fully subordinate to all the members of the group

54:03.000 --> 54:06.000
and all the resources allocated to solve this task.

54:06.000 --> 54:09.000
Clean project structures are used

54:10.000 --> 54:13.000
only to solve any large-scale tasks.

54:13.000 --> 54:16.000
Another type of project structure

54:16.000 --> 54:19.000
is called a matrix organization.

54:19.000 --> 54:22.000
The beginning of the use of a matrix organization

54:22.000 --> 54:25.000
was assumed by medium-sized aerospace companies

54:25.000 --> 54:28.000
in the 1950s and 1960s.

54:28.000 --> 54:31.000
These companies were too small

54:31.000 --> 54:34.000
to be an effective clean project organization.

54:34.000 --> 54:37.000
Nevertheless, they were large enough

54:38.000 --> 54:41.000
to face the problems of functional structures

54:41.000 --> 54:44.000
in which the integration of information about the project

54:44.000 --> 54:47.000
takes place only at the very top of the pyramid of management.

54:47.000 --> 54:50.000
Such companies as General Electric and Shell Oil

54:50.000 --> 54:53.000
conducted experiments

54:53.000 --> 54:56.000
on applying the project structure

54:56.000 --> 54:59.000
to the permanent functional structure for these organizations.

54:59.000 --> 55:02.000
The diagram of such a structure

55:02.000 --> 55:05.000
is shown in the following slide.

55:05.000 --> 55:08.000
It resembles a lattice, hence the name of the matrix structure.

55:08.000 --> 55:11.000
In a matrix organization,

55:11.000 --> 55:14.000
the members of the project group

55:14.000 --> 55:17.000
are subordinate to both the project manager

55:17.000 --> 55:20.000
and the managers of the functional departments

55:20.000 --> 55:23.000
in which they work constantly.

55:23.000 --> 55:26.000
The project manager has so-called project powers.

55:26.000 --> 55:29.000
These powers can vary

55:29.000 --> 55:32.000
from almost omnipresent personal linear power

55:32.000 --> 55:35.000
to almost pure staff powers.

55:35.000 --> 55:38.000
The choice of a specific option

55:38.000 --> 55:41.000
is determined by the rights delegated to it

55:41.000 --> 55:44.000
by the higher management of the organization.

55:44.000 --> 55:47.000
Project managers are responsible in general

55:47.000 --> 55:50.000
for the integration of all types of activities and resources

55:50.000 --> 55:53.000
related to this project.

55:53.000 --> 55:56.000
They are also responsible for planning the project

55:56.000 --> 55:59.000
and check the course of the project.

55:59.000 --> 56:02.000
The functional departments

56:02.000 --> 56:05.000
delegate some of their responsibilities to the project manager.

56:05.000 --> 56:08.000
They decide where and how a particular work should be done,

56:08.000 --> 56:11.000
as well as control the course of the task.

56:11.000 --> 56:14.000
The main drawback of the matrix structure

56:14.000 --> 56:17.000
is its complexity.

56:17.000 --> 56:20.000
A lot of problems arise

56:20.000 --> 56:23.000
due to the addition of vertical and horizontal powers,

56:23.000 --> 56:26.000
which undermines the principle of unanimity.

56:26.000 --> 56:29.000
There is a struggle for power,

56:29.000 --> 56:32.000
conformity in the adoption of group decisions,

56:32.000 --> 56:35.000
excessive overhead costs.

56:35.000 --> 56:38.000
Despite these possible difficulties,

56:38.000 --> 56:41.000
the matrix structure, if used effectively,

56:41.000 --> 56:44.000
gives the organization the opportunity

56:44.000 --> 56:47.000
to gain some advantages.

56:47.000 --> 56:50.000
It allows to achieve certain flexibilities

56:50.000 --> 56:53.000
that are never present in functional structures,

56:53.000 --> 56:56.000
but are constantly fixed

56:56.000 --> 56:59.000
behind certain functional departments.

56:59.000 --> 57:02.000
As new projects appear,

57:02.000 --> 57:05.000
labor resources can be flexibly redistributed

57:05.000 --> 57:08.000
depending on the specific needs of each project.

57:08.000 --> 57:11.000
In addition to a much greater flexibility,

57:11.000 --> 57:14.000
the matrix organization gives a greater opportunity

57:14.000 --> 57:17.000
to coordinate the work typical for division structures.

57:17.000 --> 57:20.000
This is achieved by creating a position

57:20.000 --> 57:23.000
of the project manager,

57:23.000 --> 57:26.000
who coordinates all the connections

57:26.000 --> 57:29.000
between project participants

57:29.000 --> 57:32.000
working in various functional departments.

57:32.000 --> 57:35.000
Note that in matrix organizations,

57:35.000 --> 57:38.000
the divisional command structure

57:38.000 --> 57:41.000
can have a different orientation,

57:41.000 --> 57:44.000
for example, a product one, as shown in the following slide.

57:44.000 --> 57:47.000
For companies operating on international markets,

57:47.000 --> 57:50.000
the duality of the management chain

57:50.000 --> 57:53.000
is the main reason for contradictions

57:53.000 --> 57:56.000
arising in the matrix structure.

57:56.000 --> 57:59.000
At the same time, it is successfully used

57:59.000 --> 58:02.000
by such companies as IBM, Ford Motor, and others.

58:02.000 --> 58:05.000
Another approach to creating adaptive organizational structures

58:05.000 --> 58:08.000
is associated with the emergence of a conglomerate type organization.

58:08.000 --> 58:11.000
This is not some established or orderly structure,

58:11.000 --> 58:14.000
but a type of organization

58:15.000 --> 58:18.000
that is best suited for a given specific situation.

58:18.000 --> 58:21.000
Thus, in one department of the company

58:21.000 --> 58:24.000
a product structure can be used,

58:24.000 --> 58:27.000
in another a functional structure,

58:27.000 --> 58:30.000
and in the third a project or matrix structure.

58:30.000 --> 58:33.000
The leadership of the higher link of the corporation

58:33.000 --> 58:36.000
is responsible for long-term planning,

58:36.000 --> 58:39.000
development of policy,

58:39.000 --> 58:42.000
as well as the implementation of the project.

58:42.000 --> 58:45.000
This central group is surrounded by a number of companies

58:45.000 --> 58:48.000
that are either independent economic units

58:48.000 --> 58:51.000
or in fact independent companies.

58:51.000 --> 58:54.000
These companies are fully autonomous

58:54.000 --> 58:57.000
in relation to operational decisions.

58:57.000 --> 59:00.000
They are subordinate to the main company

59:00.000 --> 59:03.000
mainly in matters of finance.

59:03.000 --> 59:06.000
It is expected that they will achieve the intended profit indicators,

59:06.000 --> 59:09.000
and that they will be able to provide a stable and stable business.

59:09.000 --> 59:12.000
It is expected that they will achieve the intended profit indicators

59:12.000 --> 59:15.000
and will keep the costs within the limits

59:15.000 --> 59:18.000
established for the entire conglomerate by the leadership of the higher link.

59:18.000 --> 59:21.000
There is almost no interdependence

59:21.000 --> 59:24.000
between the individual companies

59:24.000 --> 59:27.000
that are part of the conglomerate,

59:27.000 --> 59:30.000
unlike typical departmentalization.

59:30.000 --> 59:33.000
The conglomerate can sell any company

59:33.000 --> 59:36.000
that is part of it due to its unsatisfactory activity

59:36.000 --> 59:39.000
and will not be able to buy a company with good economic indicators.

59:39.000 --> 59:42.000
These changes will not even be noticed

59:42.000 --> 59:45.000
by other units of the conglomerate.

59:45.000 --> 59:48.000
These opportunities made the conglomerates very popular

59:48.000 --> 59:51.000
among entrepreneurs in science-intensive industries,

59:51.000 --> 59:54.000
where it is necessary to quickly switch to new types of products

59:54.000 --> 59:57.000
and quickly stop the production of outdated products.

59:57.000 --> 01:00:00.000
The latest approach to departmentalization

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:03.000
involves further development of the idea of coordination

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:07.000
and cooperation in a horizontal plane within the framework of the organization.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:10.000
The network structure means

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:13.000
that the company assigns many of its main functions

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:16.000
to independent sub-counteragents,

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:19.000
and it itself takes the form of a small head organization

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:22.000
coordinating their activities.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:25.000
The network organization is usually depicted

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:28.000
as a node or center

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:31.000
surrounded by a network of third-party entities.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:34.000
Accounting, production, design, logistics, distribution

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:37.000
and other functions are assigned to third-party organizations.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:40.000
With the help of the Internet and computer networks,

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:43.000
the exchange of information between them happens so quickly

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:46.000
that this separate system acts as a single company.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:49.000
Such a company achieves high results

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:52.000
in its activity by using the network

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:55.000
and the network of third-party entities.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:58.000
The organization is also responsible

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:01.000
for the high results of its activities

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:04.000
by using a smaller volume of resources

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:07.000
due to the fact that all the necessary special functions

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:10.000
are performed by professionals

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:13.000
with the appropriate competencies.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:16.000
The disadvantages of network structures can be attributed

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:19.000
to the lack of direct management control,

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:22.000
the possibility of undesirable loss of organizational parts,

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:25.000
low loyalty of employees

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:28.000
and the lack of a proper management of corporate culture.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:31.000
There is no optimal organization structure for all situations.

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:34.000
As in all management processes,

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:37.000
there is only the most suitable way

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:40.000
for this situation in the design of organizations.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:43.000
The relative effectiveness of a particular type

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:46.000
of organizational structure

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:49.000
is determined by various external and internal factors.

01:01:49.000 --> 01:01:52.000
If some organizations function

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:56.000
in an environment different from that of other organizations,

01:01:56.000 --> 01:01:59.000
then, accordingly, the structures should also differ.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:02.000
Another important factor in the design of an organization

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:05.000
is related to its integration

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:08.000
or, as it is often called, coordination of organizations.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:11.000
In order for our body to be healthy and agile,

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:14.000
it needs a well-coordinated muscle system,

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:17.000
a breathing system, blood circulation,

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:20.000
a nervous system, a central nervous system,

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:24.000
and the most important condition for the organization's effectiveness

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:27.000
is the unity of goals.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:30.000
It is not enough for each unit

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:33.000
to work effectively on its own.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:36.000
If one or two units are not integrated

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:39.000
in the overall structure of the organization,

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:42.000
the organization will not be successful.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:45.000
The methods of achieving effective integration

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:48.000
are shown in the following slide.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:52.000
Such methods of integration, as a rule,

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:55.000
procedures, schedules, hierarchical management structures

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:58.000
have proven to be good

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:01.000
in this type of environment

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:04.000
that characterizes by relative stability,

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:07.000
predictability,

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:10.000
slow market changes

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:13.000
of the technologies used by the competitors.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:16.000
Such methods of integration, as personal relationships,

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:20.000
joint committees,

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:23.000
inter-functional creative teams and working groups,

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:26.000
as well as inter-individual meetings,

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:29.000
have proven to be good

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:32.000
in this type of environment

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:35.000
that characterizes by mobility, variability,

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:38.000
rapid market changes and technologies used.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:41.000
If an organization or its unit

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:44.000
is characterized by the use of technologies

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:47.000
and the use of different products,

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:50.000
more diverse tasks and qualified workforce,

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:53.000
it will be possible to achieve a successful integration.

